2. Employees who are expected to respond to any NH3 release, other than a minor release, shall receive training in accordance with WAC 296-62-3112, appropriate and required for their particular level of involvement.



3. Training for the EM will occur at bi-yearly drills and subsequent critiques.



4. NH3 release responders shall conduct exercises with emergency service responders yearly.





VII    PRELIMINARY ASSESSMENT OF THE SITUATION



A    The refrigeration supervisor will assume the role of Operations Chief or Hazmat Entry Team Leader ASAP.  Incoming aid will work within ICS that is established by the HazMat Response Incident Commander.  He/she shall also initiate and maintain a log of events during an emergency. The following initial information should be added to the checklist during the preliminary assessment of the situation:



1. Assessment of incident site condition (including but not limited to condition of diked areas, surface runoff, ground condition and containment capability and environmental conditions);



2. Assessment of off site effects on human population



3. Date and time of incident (as accurately as possible);



4. Name of substance involved;



5. Ammonia concentrations measured using the ammonia detectors;



6. Estimated volume or weight of substance involved;



7. Estimated duration of release;



8. Cause of incident, if known;



9. Names of persons and agencies contacted, time contacted, description of conversation and report numbers issued; and



10. Record of control measures taken (include times of action when possible).



B    The facility's Evacuation Manager will assume the role of the Planning Chief unless the IC can fill these positions or he/she is moved to the Unif

ied IC Position. He/she assesses possible hazards both direct and indirect to human health and/or the environment or property both inside and outside of the plant 





VIII    TERMINATION AND FOLLOW-UP ACTIVITIES



A    Incident Documentation/Reporting Requirements



1. A written report may be required to be submitted to the Chelan County Local Emergency Planning Committee, Department of Ecology and the National Response Center, as soon as practicable, after the initial reporting of an NH3 release. The agency will advise you if they need a written report.



2. This written report should include:



* The name, address and telephone number of the individual that reported the release;





* The name, address and telephone number of the individual submitting the report;



* The source of the release;



* The location of the release, as follows:



      a    For  discharge  on land  or into air,  the name of the             site,  the  street  address,  the  municipality  and the             county of facility involved; or



      b    For discharge on, under or into water,  the  name  of             the  water body,  the latitude  and  longitude  of  the             place the discharge  originated and a map identifying             the areas affected by the discharge.



* The chemical name and Chemical Abstract Service (CAS) Number of each of the hazardous substances discharged     (CAS Number for NH3 is 7664-41-7); 



* The quantities of each hazardous substance discharged, including best estimates if the quantities are unknown;





* The date and time at which the discharge began, the date and time at which the discharge was discovered, the date and time at which the discharge ended and the date and time when outside agencies were notified;



* A detailed description of the actions taken;



* The corrective actions or countermeasures taken to mitigate future releases; and



* Additional preventive measures taken or proposed to minimize the possibility of recurrence.



